In August, 2011, the PI and other organizers held a successful workshop.  Approximately 50 people attended.  As of report submission time, the workshop URL was accessible at http://www.math.lsa.umich.edu/conferences/coding/index.html . The participants were surveyed and were found to be generally enthusiastic.  Example responses to "What did you hope to achieve by attending the workshop?" are below:

&bull; present new research, receive feedback, seek new ideas;

&bull; learn new techniques and ideas in sparsity, compressed sensing;

&bull; relations between compressed sensing to my own areas of interest, in particular pseudo randomness and explicit constructions;

&bull; to learn more about algorithmic problems arising in sparse approximation and compressed sensing;

&bull; learn more about recent work/ideas in compressed sensing and coding. A deeper understanding will
help me in my current research, as well as increase the breadth of my knowledge in CS theory;

A problem posed in an "open problem session" of our workshop was thereby brought to the attention of a participant, who later solved the problem; two conference papers resulted within a year.

Tutorials were presented that were of interest to the local University community, including junior researchers and researchers from under-represented gropus.

All of the survey respondents said they were "some what" or "very" likely to attend in 2012 if the workshop were to be held for a second time.  Accordingly, the workshop will indeed be held again in 2012.

